'''RAMPART-A''' is the [[code name]] for global mass surveillance and world-wide [[signals intelligence]] partnership program led by the [[United States]] [[National Security Agency]] (NSA).<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2014/06/18/nsa-surveillance-secret-cable-partners-revealed-rampart-a/|title=How Secret Partners Expand NSA’s Surveillance Dragnet|last=Ryan|first=Gallagher|date=June 19, 2014|website=The Intercept|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502020123/https://theintercept.com/2014/06/18/nsa-surveillance-secret-cable-partners-revealed-rampart-a/|archive-date=May 2, 2018|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.information.dk/udland/2014/06/nsa-third-party-partners-tap-the-internet-backbone-in-global-surveillance-program|title=NSA ‘third party’ partners tap the Internet backbone in global surveillance program|last=Anton Geist; Sebastian Gjerding; Henrik Moltke; Laura Poitras.|first=|date=19 June 2014|website=Dagbladet Information|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722111501/https://www.information.dk/udland/2014/06/nsa-third-party-partners-tap-the-internet-backbone-in-global-surveillance-program|archive-date=22 July 2018|dead-url=|access-date=4 August 2018}}</ref> Aim of the program is to "[[Upstream collection|gain access]] to high-capacity [[Submarine communications cable|international fiber-optic cables]] that transit at major congestion points around the world".<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/s3.documentcloud.org/documents/1200864/tssinframpartaoverview-v1-0-redacted-information.pdf|title=RAMPART-A Project Overview|last=|first=|date=1 October 2010|website=|type=Classified Top Secret PDF-file. Part of the published files (see the articles from Dagbladet Information[https://www.information.dk/udland/2014/06/nsa-third-party-partners-tap-the-internet-backbone-in-global-surveillance-program] and The Intercept[https://theintercept.com/2014/06/18/nsa-surveillance-secret-cable-partners-revealed-rampart-a/]).|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321194414/https://s3.amazonaws.com/s3.documentcloud.org/documents/1200864/tssinframpartaoverview-v1-0-redacted-information.pdf|archive-date=21 March 2018|dead-url=|access-date=4 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/1200860-odd-s3-overviewnov2011-v1-0-redacted-information.html|title=Special Source Operations (SSO) Overview presenting the RAMPART-A program|last=|first=|date=|website=|type=Classified Top Secret PDF-file. Part of the published files (see the articles from Dagbladet Information[https://www.information.dk/udland/2014/06/nsa-third-party-partners-tap-the-internet-backbone-in-global-surveillance-program] and The Intercept[https://theintercept.com/2014/06/18/nsa-surveillance-secret-cable-partners-revealed-rampart-a/]).|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321194347/https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/1200860-odd-s3-overviewnov2011-v1-0-redacted-information.html|archive-date=21 March 2018|dead-url=|access-date=4 August 2018}}</ref>

NSA is working with secret cooperation with the partner countries, which are hosting U.S. equipment and providing access to the fiber-optic cables.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":3" /> In 2013 the program had "access to over 3 [[Terabit|terabits]] per second of data streaming world-wide and encompasses all communication technologies such as [[Telephone call|voice]], [[fax]], [[telex]], [[modem]], [[email]] [[internet chat]], [[virtual private network]] (VPN), [[voice over IP]] (VoIP), and voice call records"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/s3.documentcloud.org/documents/1200866/foreignpartneraccessbudgetfy2013-redacted.pdf|title=Black Budget|last=|first=|date=2011|website=United States Intelligence Community|type=Classified Top Secret PDF-file. Part of the published files (see the articles from Dagbladet Information[https://www.information.dk/udland/2014/06/nsa-third-party-partners-tap-the-internet-backbone-in-global-surveillance-program] and The Intercept[https://theintercept.com/2014/06/18/nsa-surveillance-secret-cable-partners-revealed-rampart-a/]).|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321194335/https://s3.amazonaws.com/s3.documentcloud.org/documents/1200866/foreignpartneraccessbudgetfy2013-redacted.pdf|archive-date=21 March 2018|dead-url=|access-date=4 August 2018}}</ref> and there were total of 37 partner countries including 17 [[Member state of the European Union|European Union member states]].<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":0" /><ref name="Greenwald2014" />

There are two conditions on the partnership between the NSA and the partner country for making an agreement. The first one is that the partner countries will not use the NSA's technology to collect any data on U.S. citizens. The second one is that the NSA will not use the access it has been granted in the partner countries to collect data on the host countries' citizens.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /> Although these conditions have exceptions, NSA doesn't state which those exceptions are. According to [[Edward Snowden]], these agreements between the NSA and its partner countries are vague and are easily circumvented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/document/activities/cont/201403/20140307ATT80674/20140307ATT80674EN.pdf|title=Edward Snowden's testimony - European Parliament|last=|first=|date=7 March 2014|website=|page=4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621195213/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/document/activities/cont/201403/20140307ATT80674/20140307ATT80674EN.pdf|archive-date=21 June 2018|dead-url=|access-date=4 August 2018}}</ref>

The program was publicly revealed in June 2014, by the Danish newspaper ''[[Dagbladet Information]]''<ref name=":1" /> and by ''[[The Intercept]]''.<ref name=":0" /> Revelation of the program was based on as part of the [[Global surveillance disclosures (2013–present)|leaks by the former NSA contractor Edward Snowden]].

According to a NSA's classified intelligence briefing in 2010,<ref name=":2" /> RAMPART-A was used across all NSA Analysis and Production lines, and in the previous year (2009), over 9000 intelligence reports were written based solely on the RAMPART-A data.

The program cost about $170 million between 2011 and 2013.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />The program started in 1992.<ref name=":2" />

[[XKeyscore]] is implemented in the program's architecture.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/1200865-uodds2overview-v1-1-redacted-information-dk.html|title=Special Source Operations (SSO) slides with details on RAMPART-A sites, collection and tasking|last=|first=|date=|website=|type=Classified Top Secret PDF-file. Part of the published files (see the articles from Dagbladet Information[https://www.information.dk/udland/2014/06/nsa-third-party-partners-tap-the-internet-backbone-in-global-surveillance-program] and The Intercept[https://theintercept.com/2014/06/18/nsa-surveillance-secret-cable-partners-revealed-rampart-a/]).|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313201540/https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/1200865-uodds2overview-v1-1-redacted-information-dk.html|archive-date=13 March 2016|dead-url=|access-date=4 August 2018}}</ref>

== Partners ==
The partner countries are divided into two groups by their cooperation level, "Second" and "Third".<ref name="Greenwald2014">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AvFzAgAAQBAJ|title=No Place to Hide: Edward Snowden, the NSA, and the U.S. Surveillance State|author=Glenn Greenwald|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Henry Holt and Company|isbn=978-1-62779-074-1|pages=104–105|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

For the host partner country, U.S. provides processing and analysis tools and equipment, which means that the partner countries are able to use the NSA's tools for processing and analysing the data that flows in and out of their country.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /> It's likely that not every partner country has RAMPART-A site(s); in 2013 NSA had set up at least 13 RAMPART-A sites, nine of which were in active state. Three of the largest sites, ''AZUREPHOENIX'', ''SPINNERET'' and ''MOONLIGHTPATH'' gathers traffic from some 70 different cables or networks.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

Second level (partners of the [[Five Eyes]]) partner countries:

