{{Time zones of Africa}}
'''West Africa Time''', or '''WAT''', is a time zone used in west-central [[Africa]]; with countries west of [[Benin]] instead using [[Greenwich Mean Time]] (GMT; equivalent to [[UTC±0|UTC with no offset]]). West Africa Time is one hour ahead of [[Coordinated Universal Time]] ([[UTC+01:00|UTC+01]]), which makes it the same as [[Central European Time]] (CET) during winter, or [[Western European Summer Time]] (WEST) and [[British Summer Time]] (BST) during the summer.

As most of this time zone is in the [[equator]]ial and [[tropics|tropical]] region, there is little change in day length throughout the year, so [[daylight saving time]] is not observed.

West Africa Time is used by the following countries:
*{{Flag|Algeria}} (as ''Central European Time'')
*{{Flag|Angola}}
*{{Flag|Benin}}
*{{Flag|Chad}}
*{{Flag|Cameroon}}
*{{Flag|Central African Republic}}
*{{Flag|Democratic Republic of the Congo}} (western side only)
*{{Flag|Equatorial Guinea}}
*{{Flag|Gabon}}
*{{Flag|Morocco}} (as ''Greenwich Mean Time + 1 hour'')
*{{Flag|Niger}}
*{{Flag|Nigeria}}
*{{Flag|Republic of the Congo}}
*{{Flag|São Tomé and Príncipe}}
*{{Flag|Tunisia}} (as ''Central European Time'')

